msContents.summary: This manuscript is a fourteenth-century psalter, written in textualis script in northern France. Leaves with historiated initials have been removed, including the initials for Psalm 1 (before fol. 1) and Psalm 27 (before fol. 55), leaving the initials for Psalm 81 (fol. 198r) and Psalm 110 (fol. 276r). Every page has a relatively simple lateral border along the left margin in gold, blue, and pink, usually with animal or human heads at the top and bottom.

supportDesc.extent: ii+315+ii; 98 x 60 mm bound to 108 x 75 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in lead, 1-57, i, 58-314 (unnumbered leaf after fol. 57), upper right recto

collation.p: Structure uncertain; occasional catchwords and signatures almost completely trimmed away suggest mostly quires of twelve leaves with occasional quires of ten leaves

p.signatures: Trimmed signatures of letters followed by roman numerals in red, often completely trimmed away

p.catchwords: Trimmed catchwords in the gutter of the last verso of some quires

layoutDesc.layout: One column of thirteen lines; frame-ruled in lead with double upper bounding line; written area: 600 x 400 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Two historiated initials (Jesus and the doctors, fol. 198r; Pentecost, fol. 276r); borders on the left side throughout in gold with blue and pink and with zoomorphic heads as finials; three-line initial at the beginning of each psalm and one-line initial at the beginning of each verse in gold on blue and pink ground with white tracery; line fillers in gold with blue and red penwork; rubrication in red
Inside front coverPrinted bookplate, Ettington Manuscript Library
198rHistoriated initial Q, Jesus among the doctors

binding.p: Nineteenth-century morocco, gilt-tooled, with parchment flyleaves; spine damaged at top and bottom, headband and tailband exposed and broken

history.provenance: Robert B. Wheeler, Stratford-on-Avon (inscription in ink, front flyleaf i recto); Ettington Manuscript Library (Evelyn Philip Shirley, near Stratford-on-Avon), no. 4 (bookplate, inside front cover)
